WEBVTT

00:01.083 --> 00:04.792
♪

00:06.000 --> 00:08.458
♪

00:08.458 --> 00:09.875
Hi.

00:09.875 --> 00:11.542
-Hi.
-Hey, Jen!

00:11.542 --> 00:14.250
Oh, thank you so much
for doing this.

00:14.250 --> 00:16.500
It’s so great to have
a lawyer in the family.

00:16.500 --> 00:19.208
Well, of course, well,
when Heather volunteered me,

00:19.208 --> 00:22.250
-what could I say out loud?
-Well, it is embarrassing.

00:22.250 --> 00:25.750
I just assumed we had a will,
but apparently not.

00:25.750 --> 00:28.000
Um, John thinks
that they cause death.

00:28.000 --> 00:30.291
Well, I do know a lot
of people who died,

00:30.291 --> 00:32.500
and every one of them
had a will.

00:32.500 --> 00:34.000
-Do the math.
-Right.

00:34.000 --> 00:35.333
Yeah, no, that adds up.

00:35.333 --> 00:37.208
Well, you--you have
a will now, too,

00:37.208 --> 00:40.250
and, um, I put everything
in there that you asked for--

00:40.250 --> 00:41.625
Not everything.

00:41.625 --> 00:45.709
Uh, I wanted to add
a couple of zingers.

00:45.709 --> 00:47.875
-"Zingers"?
-Well, with both of us dead,

00:47.875 --> 00:49.291
it’s gonna be kind of a sad day,

00:49.291 --> 00:51.458
and I want people
to enjoy themselves.

00:51.458 --> 00:54.125
JOAN: Yeah, it--it’s why
he wants our ashes

00:54.125 --> 00:55.625
shot out of a T-shirt gun.

00:55.625 --> 00:58.083
JOHN: Yeah, how about
we start with this?

00:58.083 --> 01:00.625
"We leave everything
to our fish,"

01:00.625 --> 01:02.542
and then you say, "Psych!"

01:02.542 --> 01:04.792
Yeah, no, little problem
is that, uh,

01:04.792 --> 01:07.709
you can’t really put "psych"
in a--in a legal document.

01:07.709 --> 01:10.166
-Oh. Oh, okay.
-Oh. Yeah, I understand.

01:10.166 --> 01:13.542
How about just, "We leave
everything to our fish."

01:14.792 --> 01:16.875
"Not!"

01:16.875 --> 01:19.250
Yeah, you guys could go
all night.

01:19.250 --> 01:20.500
Once I leave.

01:20.500 --> 01:23.709
Now is this distributed equally,
or is it based on dire need?

01:23.709 --> 01:25.125
Oh, don’t worry,
I’m sure the new owners

01:25.125 --> 01:26.500
will let you stay
in the garage.

01:26.500 --> 01:28.041
HEATHER: I don’t care
about the money.

01:28.041 --> 01:30.250
I just--I want
all of the photo albums.

01:30.250 --> 01:31.291
Oh, that’s sweet.

01:31.291 --> 01:33.083
No, I--I need
to destroy the evidence

01:33.083 --> 01:35.125
of the year that
I only wore men’s suits.

01:35.125 --> 01:37.667
Oh, that’s right,
that’s the year I wore do-rags.

01:37.667 --> 01:39.417
-I looked good.
HEATHER: Oh!

01:39.417 --> 01:43.166
And, Greg, you wore overalls
and sideways painter’s caps.

01:43.166 --> 01:45.083
Yeah, people called me
Dutchy Boy.

01:45.083 --> 01:46.750
Okay, but seriously,
Jen, what’s in it?

01:46.750 --> 01:48.667
Uh, no, I can’t tell you that.

01:48.667 --> 01:50.250
I mean, it’s
attorney-client privilege.

01:50.250 --> 01:52.041
Yeah, but that doesn’t apply
to families, does it?

01:52.041 --> 01:53.834
Uh, I’ll tell you a secret.
You want to know a secret?

01:53.834 --> 01:56.500
I’ll tell you one right now:
Tim pees sitting down.

01:56.500 --> 01:58.208
If I’m in there,
I’m doing the word jumble.

01:58.208 --> 01:59.500
Period.

01:59.500 --> 02:02.166
♪

02:02.166 --> 02:04.500
Okay, here are the executed
copies for your files.

02:04.500 --> 02:08.417
Uh, is it too late to add in
"of sound mind and dope body"?

02:08.417 --> 02:10.166
(snickering)

02:10.166 --> 02:11.250
Yes.

02:11.250 --> 02:13.834
Ooh, I didn’t realize
it costs so much.

02:13.834 --> 02:14.834
What? Oh, no, I’m sorry.

02:14.834 --> 02:16.542
That invoice was not
supposed to be in there.

02:16.542 --> 02:18.500
Is that what you make per hour?

02:18.500 --> 02:19.542
What do the men get?

02:21.166 --> 02:22.542
Um...

02:22.542 --> 02:24.667
No, I’m not--
I’m not charging you.

02:24.667 --> 02:26.542
Yeah, you’re family.

02:26.542 --> 02:28.375
Oh, don’t tell Matt that.

02:28.375 --> 02:29.542
I just raised his rent.

02:29.542 --> 02:32.000
♪

02:32.000 --> 02:33.834
I don’t understand
what the big deal is.

02:33.834 --> 02:35.417
That Heather
volunteered you for this,

02:35.417 --> 02:36.709
and now we’re stuck
paying for it.

02:36.709 --> 02:38.125
Yeah, but it’s not
even that much money.

02:38.125 --> 02:39.917
It’s just, like, filing costs
and paralegal fees.

02:39.917 --> 02:41.875
No, but it’s not
about the money.

02:41.875 --> 02:43.458
I’ve always wanted
to call the shots.

02:43.458 --> 02:44.917
My whole life,
Heather and Matt

02:44.917 --> 02:46.083
have been telling me
what to do,

02:46.083 --> 02:47.583
and now they’re telling
my wife what to do.

02:47.583 --> 02:49.792
I can’t have that.
No, they got to pay.

02:49.792 --> 02:51.500
I thought you just said
it wasn’t about the money.

02:51.500 --> 02:53.375
No, it’s not,
but, in this case, it is.

02:53.375 --> 02:55.625
But that’s just a coincidence.

02:55.625 --> 02:57.417
Okay, listen, here’s the deal.

02:57.417 --> 02:58.667
I’ll go along with this,

02:58.667 --> 03:01.333
as long as next time
my mom calls me, you answer.

03:01.333 --> 03:03.250
So you’ll be my ally.

03:03.250 --> 03:04.083
Uh, sure.

03:05.291 --> 03:10.125
♪

03:10.125 --> 03:11.250
What’s up?

03:13.291 --> 03:16.041
You’re just waiting for somebody
to say something, aren’t you?

03:16.041 --> 03:17.000
About what?

03:17.000 --> 03:19.375
GREG: So, uh, I’d like
to thank you all for coming.

03:19.375 --> 03:20.583
Uh, I know that
we told Mom and Dad

03:20.583 --> 03:21.750
that we’d pay for their will,

03:21.750 --> 03:24.291
but turns out there are
some administrative fees.

03:24.291 --> 03:26.041
So, uh, evenly divided,

03:26.041 --> 03:28.792
this is what Jen and I
feel that you guys owe.

03:28.792 --> 03:32.834
JEN: Yes, and we both feel
that with equal conviction.

03:32.834 --> 03:36.041
-That’s right.
MATT: Oh, uh, no.

03:36.041 --> 03:38.125
Uh, I’m not paying for that.
You offered, you pay.

03:38.125 --> 03:39.667
Well, actually,
Heather offered up Jen.

03:39.667 --> 03:41.041
HEATHER:
So?

03:41.041 --> 03:42.875
We do things all the time
for the family

03:42.875 --> 03:44.041
that actually cost money.

03:44.041 --> 03:45.750
We don’t charge you guys
for any of it.

03:45.750 --> 03:47.458
-This is different.
-You’re different.

03:47.458 --> 03:49.291
Yeah, I--I helped Dad
paint the house,

03:49.291 --> 03:50.709
and I didn’t charge him
for that.

03:50.709 --> 03:52.333
Yes, you did.
You charged him $600.

03:52.333 --> 03:53.792
Well, I didn’t know
that you knew that.

03:53.792 --> 03:55.250
That kind of weakens
my argument.

03:55.250 --> 03:57.583
♪

03:57.583 --> 03:59.291
Another amazing meal, Heather.

03:59.291 --> 04:00.333
HEATHER:
Oh, thanks, Dad.

04:01.375 --> 04:02.542
For you, sir.

04:02.542 --> 04:05.250
And I can give
your wife the receipt.

04:05.250 --> 04:06.417
-What’s this?
-Oh!

04:06.417 --> 04:08.458
Well, since
you decided to charge

04:08.458 --> 04:10.375
for the things that we share,
we thought it was only fair

04:10.375 --> 04:13.166
to split the cost of this meal,
you know, equally.

04:13.166 --> 04:15.125
See, this is why
I said we should pay.

04:15.125 --> 04:16.917
HEATHER: You know,
I didn’t charge for my time,

04:16.917 --> 04:19.792
but there were, unfortunately,
some unavoidable fees.

04:19.792 --> 04:20.917
Oh, okay.

04:20.917 --> 04:23.250
SOPHIA: Sorry, hon,
I know times are tough,

04:23.250 --> 04:25.625
so dessert is on the house.

04:25.625 --> 04:26.625
What’s going on?

04:26.625 --> 04:28.250
Oh, someone’s just trying
to prove a point

04:28.250 --> 04:30.083
because I tried
to save you from incurring

04:30.083 --> 04:31.875
an expense on your will.

04:31.875 --> 04:34.792
Something that Jen was
completely on board for.

04:34.792 --> 04:36.291
Yes, and I am thrilled.

04:36.291 --> 04:38.542
Look at how it’s bringing us
so much closer together.

04:38.542 --> 04:40.542
Well, if Jen wants
the money this much.

04:40.542 --> 04:41.917
-Oh, please.
-No, I don’t.

04:41.917 --> 04:44.000
-This is not for me.
-I thought you were my ally.

04:44.000 --> 04:45.250
MATT: Whoa, whoa, whoa,
whoa, whoa, whoa!

04:45.250 --> 04:46.625
Oh, this is not even fair.

04:46.625 --> 04:47.750
I brought the wine.

04:47.750 --> 04:49.542
And that wine
was from our rack.

04:49.542 --> 04:50.834
I didn’t know
that you knew that.

04:50.834 --> 04:52.959
We all know that.

04:52.959 --> 04:54.291
GREG: I knew about
the paint job,

04:54.291 --> 04:56.500
-I know about the wine.
JOAN: Stop. Stop.

04:56.500 --> 04:59.625
You know, I--I would hope
that after we’re gone,

04:59.625 --> 05:01.542
you kids would
come closer together

05:01.542 --> 05:02.792
and not behave like this.

05:02.792 --> 05:05.083
-No, Greg started it.
-It was totally Greg.

05:05.083 --> 05:07.125
GREG: What? I didn’t
do anything, what are you--

05:07.125 --> 05:08.333
Okay, you know what? Listen.

05:08.333 --> 05:09.583
This is my fault.

05:09.583 --> 05:11.959
Yeah, I--I made Greg
ask for the money

05:11.959 --> 05:16.166
because I am secretly...
greedy,

05:16.166 --> 05:18.208
and, uh, now I regret that,

05:18.208 --> 05:22.583
because you loving sisters
and brothers are fighting.

05:22.583 --> 05:25.583
So I--I hope that you
can all forgive me

05:25.583 --> 05:27.709
for creating this problem

05:27.709 --> 05:30.875
in your always peaceful family.

05:30.875 --> 05:33.125
♪

05:33.125 --> 05:35.041
I forgive you.

05:35.041 --> 05:36.250
(chuckles)

05:36.250 --> 05:38.208
Thank you, you are a big man.

05:38.208 --> 05:41.709
♪

05:41.709 --> 05:43.125
HEATHER: Jen, come on,
it’s not your fault.

05:43.125 --> 05:45.333
No. Look, we got carried away.

05:45.333 --> 05:46.583
JOAN: Well, your father and I

05:46.583 --> 05:48.083
are glad that
the fighting has stopped,

05:48.083 --> 05:49.834
but it really doesn’t
matter anyway,

05:49.834 --> 05:52.542
because we’ve decided to leave
all the money to charity.

05:52.542 --> 05:54.625
-Oh.
-Okay, that is...

05:54.625 --> 05:56.166
Psych!

05:56.166 --> 05:58.083
(laughing)

05:58.083 --> 05:59.500
Is that better than "not"?

05:59.500 --> 06:01.041
That was perfect.

06:01.041 --> 06:04.500
(mixed chatter)

06:04.500 --> 06:05.750
Yes!

06:05.750 --> 06:07.625
♪

06:07.625 --> 06:09.333
Okay, kiddos, today we decide

06:09.333 --> 06:11.166
where we go
for family vacation.

06:11.166 --> 06:13.417
We should use our vacation
to take care of the Earth.

06:13.417 --> 06:15.500
You know, like,
pick up trash in the forest

06:15.500 --> 06:16.792
or in local streets.

06:16.792 --> 06:18.208
Honey, I am so proud of you

06:18.208 --> 06:20.834
for being such a good citizen,
but that is no vacation.

06:20.834 --> 06:22.166
That is how
they punish prisoners.

06:22.166 --> 06:23.667
You guys say you care
about the Earth,

06:23.667 --> 06:25.834
but you’re not willing
to give up your vacation for it.

06:25.834 --> 06:27.041
-That is accurate.
-I never said

06:27.041 --> 06:28.709
I cared about the Earth.

06:28.709 --> 06:32.667
How about we put it to the test
with a bet?

06:32.667 --> 06:34.291
Ugh, you know betting
is my weakness.

06:34.291 --> 06:36.333
All right, what kind of odds
are we talking here?

06:36.333 --> 06:39.125
For one day, everyone
carries around a trash bag,

06:39.125 --> 06:40.500
and all their trash
goes into it.

06:40.500 --> 06:41.709
At the end of the day,

06:41.709 --> 06:44.041
whoever has the least
amount of trash wins.

06:44.041 --> 06:46.250
And that person gets to pick
where we go on vacation.

06:46.250 --> 06:47.291
Yeah, I like it.

06:47.291 --> 06:50.000
All right, this starts now.

06:50.000 --> 06:51.875
I am going to win
this so easily,

06:51.875 --> 06:53.458
because you guys have no idea

06:53.458 --> 06:55.041
how much trash you create,

06:55.041 --> 06:56.875
because I am the one
who always picks it up.

06:56.875 --> 06:59.792
So at the end of the day,
my bag is going to be empty.

06:59.792 --> 07:01.458
Can you hold that, please?

07:01.458 --> 07:02.750
Gotcha.

07:02.750 --> 07:04.542
Dang it, uh, Sophia?

07:05.917 --> 07:07.083
Shaking my head.

07:07.083 --> 07:09.000
♪

07:10.000 --> 07:17.333
♪

07:17.333 --> 07:20.041
(toilet flushes)

07:20.041 --> 07:21.500
(doorbell rings)

07:21.500 --> 07:23.750
Hey, Dad, your Gene Simmons
bobbleheads are here.

07:23.750 --> 07:25.709
TIM:
Ooh! Awesome, can’t wait.

07:25.709 --> 07:26.667
Oh, wait a minute.

07:26.667 --> 07:28.750
That thing’s gonna be filled
with Styrofoam peanuts.

07:28.750 --> 07:30.041
I just know it.

07:30.041 --> 07:31.750
Sorry. Can’t accept it.

07:31.750 --> 07:32.750
You’re not Mr. Hughes?

07:32.750 --> 07:34.250
No, I’m Dr. Hughes.

07:34.250 --> 07:35.750
-This is Mr. Hughes.
-No, no, no.

07:35.750 --> 07:37.125
I’m not 18,
you can’t make me.

07:37.125 --> 07:38.291
Excuse me.

07:38.291 --> 07:39.208
I’ll sign that.

07:41.250 --> 07:42.250
Thank you.

07:42.250 --> 07:44.125
-She’s not Mr. Hughes.
-Thank you.

07:44.125 --> 07:45.709
All right, well,
here you go, Mr. Winner.

07:45.709 --> 07:47.667
Now, I’m pretty sure
there’s some extra packing

07:47.667 --> 07:49.083
in there
for Gene’s spinal column.

07:49.083 --> 07:51.542
So, yeah, you enjoy that.

07:51.542 --> 07:52.500
Son.

07:53.875 --> 07:56.041
What are we doing here?

07:56.041 --> 07:58.709
Separately, we are weak,
but together,

07:58.709 --> 08:00.542
we could be less weak,
you know what I’m saying?

08:00.542 --> 08:03.375
Sorry, Dad, I already formed
an alliance with Mom.

08:03.375 --> 08:05.834
She offered to do my laundry
for life, so...

08:05.834 --> 08:07.000
Yeah, that’s pretty good.

08:07.000 --> 08:13.333
♪

08:13.333 --> 08:16.375
(toilet flushes)

08:16.375 --> 08:19.709
♪

08:19.709 --> 08:21.166
Uh, you don’t mind

08:21.166 --> 08:23.250
if I check
your guitar case, do you?

08:23.250 --> 08:24.583
Seriously?

08:24.583 --> 08:25.750
Mom, you gonna let her do that?

08:25.750 --> 08:27.959
Oh, sure, go crying
to your mommy.

08:27.959 --> 08:31.250
See if she can’t fluff
and fold your problems away.

08:31.250 --> 08:32.709
Ow!

08:32.709 --> 08:34.417
See?

08:34.417 --> 08:36.792
Some things are
more important to me

08:36.792 --> 08:38.250
than choosing a vacation.

08:39.375 --> 08:41.250
Like honesty and trust.

08:43.959 --> 08:47.792
Busted! You have trash
in your pants.

08:47.792 --> 08:49.792
I--yeah, well, I bet
you have trash in your bra.

08:49.792 --> 08:51.083
TIM:
He should have to eat it!

08:51.083 --> 08:52.458
With his mouth!

08:52.458 --> 08:57.417
♪

08:57.417 --> 08:58.875
My car blew a tire.

09:00.417 --> 09:02.375
Well, alliance is over,
good luck.

09:02.375 --> 09:03.834
What?

09:03.834 --> 09:05.375
(stammering)

09:05.375 --> 09:10.834
♪

09:10.834 --> 09:13.542
(toilet flushing, bubbling)

09:13.542 --> 09:14.709
SOPHIA:
Uh-oh.

09:14.709 --> 09:16.959
Dad!

09:16.959 --> 09:19.166
The only good thing
that can come out of this

09:19.166 --> 09:21.667
is I can see my fish again.

09:22.458 --> 09:23.583
TIM:
Hey!

09:23.583 --> 09:25.000
What’s going on?

09:25.000 --> 09:26.583
It won’t flush.

09:26.583 --> 09:28.083
I think we need
a bigger toilet.

09:28.083 --> 09:29.166
Yeah.

09:29.166 --> 09:30.458
I’ve been saying that
for years.

09:30.458 --> 09:31.792
Let’s take
a little look-see here.

09:33.417 --> 09:34.542
Whoa, whoa, whoa!

09:34.542 --> 09:37.083
Why is there a Cheesy Chip bag
in this toilet?

09:37.083 --> 09:39.750
You know those things
go right through me, Dad.

09:39.750 --> 09:42.542
I cannot believe
you’ve been cheating.

09:42.542 --> 09:44.417
You know, one day that’s not
gonna be so cute anymore.

09:44.417 --> 09:48.291
Or--or we could form
an alliance.

09:48.291 --> 09:50.000
If you take my trash, I can win.

09:50.000 --> 09:51.792
Then we can go
wherever you want.

09:55.875 --> 09:58.250
How do I know
I can trust you?

09:58.250 --> 10:00.000
I don’t know.
You really don’t.

10:01.709 --> 10:03.250
All right, I’m in.

10:04.792 --> 10:06.917
Forty pounds for Mom,

10:06.917 --> 10:08.917
22 pounds for Daddy,

10:08.917 --> 10:13.125
two pounds for Tyler,
and 0.7 pounds for me.

10:13.125 --> 10:14.333
SOPHIA:
Forgot mine.

10:14.333 --> 10:17.792
♪

10:17.792 --> 10:20.291
SAMANTHA:
0.3 pounds.

10:20.291 --> 10:21.542
Sophia’s the winner.

10:21.542 --> 10:23.208
TIM:
Yes! All right!

10:23.208 --> 10:25.250
I am so glad your hamster
didn’t die today.

10:25.250 --> 10:26.750
So, where are we going
on vacation?

10:26.750 --> 10:29.500
HEATHER:
Vegas, baby! Yeah.

10:29.500 --> 10:30.750
TIM: What?

10:30.750 --> 10:31.959
Secret alliance.

10:31.959 --> 10:34.333
When you give birth to them,
they are very loyal to you.

10:34.333 --> 10:35.750
You double-crossed me?

10:35.750 --> 10:36.750
It’s okay, Daddy.

10:36.750 --> 10:38.125
I double-crossed Mommy, too.

10:38.125 --> 10:38.875
What?

10:40.917 --> 10:43.375
TIM: Oh, 45 minutes
in line to ride

10:43.375 --> 10:46.041
a plastic pig
that smells like pee?

10:46.041 --> 10:47.291
I take it back,
picking up trash

10:47.291 --> 10:48.458
would’ve been better than this.

10:48.458 --> 10:49.792
No, it’s fine, it’s fine.

10:49.792 --> 10:51.500
Forty-five minutes is not
that long to wait.

10:55.625 --> 10:57.291
(groaning)

10:57.291 --> 10:58.875
Come on.

10:58.875 --> 11:01.417
♪

11:02.291 --> 11:04.083
♪

11:04.083 --> 11:05.542
If it’s your life story,

11:05.542 --> 11:07.125
and--and you looked
like a beaver...

11:07.125 --> 11:09.208
-I did.
-...then why is the book

11:09.208 --> 11:10.208
about a chicken?

11:10.208 --> 11:13.458
Because if you Google
<i>The Beaver Who Could Chew,</i>

11:13.458 --> 11:15.125
inappropriate images come up.

11:15.125 --> 11:15.959
-Right.
-Yeah.

11:19.000 --> 11:21.959
♪

11:21.959 --> 11:23.333
So, I have good news.

11:23.333 --> 11:24.750
-Ooh.
-Remember my friend

11:24.750 --> 11:25.750
from high school, Grace?

11:25.750 --> 11:27.166
Yeah, the, uh--
the immigration lawyer

11:27.166 --> 11:29.041
who started that upside-down
cupcake business?

11:29.041 --> 11:30.542
No. Who is that?

11:30.542 --> 11:31.667
I don’t know anyone like that.

11:31.667 --> 11:32.917
-Grace is a publisher.
-Oh.

11:32.917 --> 11:34.667
So she was talking to me
about her, uh, new position

11:34.667 --> 11:36.083
in children’s books,
and I pitched her

11:36.083 --> 11:37.834
that idea that I’ve had forever.

11:37.834 --> 11:38.917
She wants me to write the book.

11:38.917 --> 11:39.834
What? Are you serious?

11:39.834 --> 11:41.000
That’s amazing!

11:41.000 --> 11:42.458
And, no, best of all,

11:42.458 --> 11:44.291
when I told her I had
a boyfriend who was an artist,

11:44.291 --> 11:46.125
who could do
killer illustrations,

11:46.125 --> 11:48.458
she said, "Great."

11:48.458 --> 11:49.375
Great!

11:49.375 --> 11:51.417
WAITRESS: Here you go.

11:51.417 --> 11:52.959
You don’t want to do it?

11:52.959 --> 11:54.667
Um, I mean, I don’t know.

11:54.667 --> 11:57.625
I’m--I’m pretty immersed
in my sketch series

11:57.625 --> 11:59.667
about human trafficking
and genocide,

11:59.667 --> 12:01.250
and so I--I just, you know,
I think that doing

12:01.250 --> 12:02.959
a bunch of kiddie drawings
would just frankly,

12:02.959 --> 12:05.250
well, it would depress me.

12:05.250 --> 12:08.542
She said if all goes well,
it could pay, like, 10 grand.

12:08.542 --> 12:10.208
MATT:<i> And I went ahead</i>
<i>and started to work</i>

12:10.208 --> 12:12.083
on some of the ancillary
characters in our book.

12:12.083 --> 12:14.917
There’s, um, there’s a cute
but lactose intolerant cow,

12:14.917 --> 12:16.667
a very pretty
but nosy mini-horse.

12:16.667 --> 12:17.792
Don’t worry, the, um,

12:17.792 --> 12:19.458
the sexual chemistry there
is just subtext.

12:19.458 --> 12:21.709
Cool, cool, cool,
but my book is called

12:21.709 --> 12:23.959
<i>-The Chicken Who Could Chew.</i>
-Right.

12:23.959 --> 12:25.750
A chicken with big teeth

12:25.750 --> 12:28.000
rubbing it in the face
of all the toothless chickens.

12:29.250 --> 12:31.041
She can eat bagels.

12:31.041 --> 12:31.959
We have to show that.

12:31.959 --> 12:33.542
Right, but our book
needs to be more

12:33.542 --> 12:35.000
than just
about a chicken eating.

12:35.000 --> 12:37.375
It needs to show the reality
of being livestock

12:37.375 --> 12:39.333
in today’s
rough-and-tumble world.

12:39.333 --> 12:42.083
Yeah, I’m not really a fan
of rough-and-tumble for my book.

12:42.083 --> 12:45.458
I’m thinking
more feathery and cute.

12:45.458 --> 12:46.625
I’m noticing this weird thing

12:46.625 --> 12:48.250
that you keep doing,
where, you know,

12:48.250 --> 12:50.959
I--I keep saying "our book"
and you keep saying "my book."

12:50.959 --> 12:53.333
Oh, right, I’m--I’m sorry.

12:53.333 --> 12:54.667
-Mhm.
-That is weird.

12:54.667 --> 12:56.625
I mean, they are
my illustrations, so, um...

12:56.625 --> 12:58.834
Right. They are
your illustrations...

12:58.834 --> 13:01.792
-Uh-huh.
-...but it’s my life story.

13:01.792 --> 13:04.750
I got my adult teeth
when I was six years old.

13:04.750 --> 13:06.500
I looked like a beaver.

13:06.500 --> 13:09.333
Everyone made fun of me,
but my mom told me to be proud

13:09.333 --> 13:11.750
and show everyone what me
and my big teeth could do.

13:11.750 --> 13:14.166
If it’s your life story,
and--and you looked

13:14.166 --> 13:15.917
-like a beaver...
-I did.

13:15.917 --> 13:18.333
...then why is the book
about a chicken?

13:18.333 --> 13:21.417
Because if you Google
<i>The Beaver Who Could Chew,</i>

13:21.417 --> 13:23.417
inappropriate images come up.

13:23.417 --> 13:24.375
-Right.
-Yeah.

13:24.375 --> 13:26.792
These--these drawings
are depressing.

13:26.792 --> 13:29.041
And these animals are,
like, third-world skinny.

13:29.041 --> 13:31.125
That pig, I really think,
should be fat.

13:31.125 --> 13:33.041
No, but the cat’s fat,
the cat with the bag of money

13:33.041 --> 13:35.041
and the--the sash
that says "foreign oil."

13:35.041 --> 13:36.417
What if you drew
something like this?

13:36.417 --> 13:38.583
And you’re taking my pencil,
and, oh, good, an eraser--

13:38.583 --> 13:40.250
that’s not gonna do any dam--

13:40.250 --> 13:42.667
COLLEEN: Calm down. I’m not
redoing it-- I’m just fixing it.

13:42.667 --> 13:44.709
Um, just out of curiosity,
how are the kids gonna know

13:44.709 --> 13:46.583
that that goat is dead
if the flies-flies aren’t there?

13:46.583 --> 13:48.166
You’ve got to be able
to take criticism, Matt.

13:48.166 --> 13:49.792
And you’ve got to find
yourself an illustrator

13:49.792 --> 13:51.542
who is willing to sell out
the integrity of his art.

13:51.542 --> 13:53.083
You can take away my flies,

13:53.083 --> 13:54.917
but you can’t take away
my freedom!

13:54.917 --> 13:57.166
(doorknob rattling)

13:57.166 --> 13:58.792
Mom? Can you open
the door, please?

14:00.792 --> 14:02.375
It’s like she was
my boss again,

14:02.375 --> 14:04.834
you know, telling me what to do.

14:04.834 --> 14:06.000
JOAN: Oh.

14:06.000 --> 14:08.500
Oh, I think this
might be my fault.

14:08.500 --> 14:11.458
I’m afraid I forced you
to choose a strong woman.

14:11.458 --> 14:14.291
Well, the same thing happened
to Greg with Jen, you know?

14:14.291 --> 14:17.250
Who’s bold and wonderful
and opinionated

14:17.250 --> 14:20.500
in nearly all our interactions.

14:20.500 --> 14:21.583
But it’s fun.

14:21.583 --> 14:23.667
It--oh, it’s fun!

14:23.667 --> 14:26.000
Colleen’s strong,
that’s for sure.

14:26.000 --> 14:29.500
I don’t think you’d be happy
with somebody who wasn’t.

14:29.500 --> 14:32.000
And keeping your relationship

14:32.000 --> 14:35.959
is a lot more important than
keeping your dinosaur drawings.

14:35.959 --> 14:38.709
-Chickens.
-Oh.

14:38.709 --> 14:41.500
Oh, well,
then Colleen’s definitely right.

14:41.500 --> 14:43.000
You need to do a better job.

14:45.792 --> 14:49.667
♪

14:49.667 --> 14:51.834
COLLEEN: What is this?

14:51.834 --> 14:55.041
This is I’m sorry.

14:55.041 --> 14:56.500
Oh.

14:56.500 --> 14:58.208
I don’t want
to argue over something

14:58.208 --> 15:00.375
that’s actually
a good thing, so...

15:00.375 --> 15:03.417
I made what you wanted.

15:03.417 --> 15:04.750
Well, it’s very sweet,

15:04.750 --> 15:06.250
but I felt bad about
changing your work,

15:06.250 --> 15:08.125
so I went ahead and sent
in the original drawings,

15:08.125 --> 15:09.291
and they loved them.

15:09.291 --> 15:10.333
-Really?
-Yeah.

15:10.333 --> 15:12.792
-They’re gonna make your book?
-They’re making<i> our </i>book.

15:12.792 --> 15:14.458
They loved the realism,

15:14.458 --> 15:15.834
and they thought it was
a fresh new take

15:15.834 --> 15:17.458
on the struggles of
toothless livestock.

15:17.458 --> 15:19.625
-That’s amazing.
-Yeah.

15:19.625 --> 15:21.041
So what are we gonna do
with all these cute

15:21.041 --> 15:22.000
little chubby animals?

15:23.625 --> 15:25.750
We’re gonna use them
for the sequel:

15:25.750 --> 15:27.542
<i>The Chicken</i>
<i>Who Chewed Too Much.</i>

15:27.542 --> 15:29.625
Shining a light on
the obesity epidemic in America.

15:29.625 --> 15:31.125
COLLEEN:
Okay, I like it.

15:31.125 --> 15:32.750
And that little sheep
on the tractor already has

15:32.750 --> 15:34.500
-a seat belt extender.
-Yeah!

15:34.500 --> 15:35.750
Ooh, let’s draw on
a little top hat.

15:35.750 --> 15:38.291
-I don’t know, maybe...
-I just think it’d be cute.

15:38.291 --> 15:40.291
...maybe we don’t do it
quite yet.

15:40.291 --> 15:41.500
Okay.

15:41.500 --> 15:44.166
♪

15:44.166 --> 15:47.208
Now, what pressure
do you prefer?

15:47.208 --> 15:49.333
Lot of pressure, lot of lotion.

15:49.333 --> 15:52.375
You know, dress me like a salad,
beat me like an egg,

15:55.750 --> 15:58.208
♪

15:58.208 --> 15:59.333
-Hi.
JOAN: Hi!

15:59.333 --> 16:02.083
-Sorry we’re late.
-Hey, where’s Greg?

16:02.083 --> 16:03.083
Huh?

16:04.792 --> 16:06.333
Oh, damn it, I forgot Greg.

16:06.333 --> 16:08.542
You know, I thought he was quiet
on the ride over.

16:08.542 --> 16:10.166
I just assumed
he was eating taffy.

16:10.166 --> 16:11.625
Even though I’ve never
seen him eat taffy.

16:11.625 --> 16:13.333
In fact, we have
no taffy in the house.

16:13.333 --> 16:14.375
I’m very tired.

16:17.291 --> 16:18.250
(door slamming)

16:18.250 --> 16:19.750
-Wow.
-Yeah.

16:19.750 --> 16:21.583
I went to go talk
to the roofer,

16:21.583 --> 16:24.291
and you just cold forgot me.

16:24.291 --> 16:25.709
Yeah. Cold-blooded.

16:25.709 --> 16:27.583
Yeah, and that’s Mommy’s bad,
but you know what?

16:27.583 --> 16:28.834
This is what happens
when you sleep

16:28.834 --> 16:30.333
-in 15-minute intervals.
-Yeah.

16:30.333 --> 16:32.583
You know what really
helps me to sleep

16:32.583 --> 16:33.750
is being 70.

16:34.959 --> 16:36.250
Gonna look into that.

16:36.250 --> 16:38.875
I just hate to see you both
so stressed out.

16:38.875 --> 16:39.834
Here, I just...

16:40.917 --> 16:43.166
...want you to use this.

16:43.166 --> 16:44.542
It’s a gift certificate

16:44.542 --> 16:47.709
for a couple’s massage
at a day spa,

16:47.709 --> 16:49.583
and we don’t want it.

16:49.583 --> 16:51.750
But we gave this to you
for your anniversary.

16:51.750 --> 16:53.208
Oh!

16:53.208 --> 16:56.083
Well, we were just waiting
to use it until

16:56.083 --> 16:58.083
we were really stressed out.

16:58.083 --> 17:01.792
But we cope by baking bread
or, you know, doing yoga

17:01.792 --> 17:04.792
or taking
spontaneous naps and...

17:04.792 --> 17:06.750
(snoring)

17:06.750 --> 17:08.709
Sometimes I draw on his face,

17:08.709 --> 17:12.333
but then I feel guilty
and wash it off.

17:12.333 --> 17:14.125
He sleeps through
the whole thing.

17:14.709 --> 17:18.000
♪

17:18.000 --> 17:20.834
Now, what pressure
do you prefer?

17:20.834 --> 17:23.041
Lot of pressure, lot of lotion.

17:23.041 --> 17:25.000
You know, dress me like a salad,

17:25.000 --> 17:26.667
beat me like an egg.

17:26.667 --> 17:28.709
Oh, and when I start crying,

17:28.709 --> 17:30.583
don’t acknowledge it, all right?

17:30.583 --> 17:31.709
I’ll stop eventually.

17:31.709 --> 17:32.834
-Thanks.
-Okay.

17:32.834 --> 17:37.917
♪

17:37.917 --> 17:39.834
(exhales)

17:39.834 --> 17:41.291
I love you, honey.

17:41.291 --> 17:44.250
I love you, too.

17:44.250 --> 17:45.458
(tires screeching, crashing)

17:45.458 --> 17:46.875
MAN: Oh, my God!

17:46.875 --> 17:49.333
(people screaming)

17:49.333 --> 17:50.417
That did not sound good.

17:50.417 --> 17:51.917
No, that sounded
really, really bad.

17:51.917 --> 17:54.875
Shh, I’m sure it was just
a little fender bender.

17:54.875 --> 17:56.375
-Should we do something?
GREG: Yeah, I mean,

17:56.375 --> 17:57.625
I sort of feel like
I should go out there

17:57.625 --> 17:59.125
-and make sure everybody’s okay.
MASSEUSE: Shh.

17:59.125 --> 18:00.291
WOMAN: Somebody help!

18:00.291 --> 18:04.750
People just need to get used
to the new stop sign.

18:04.750 --> 18:06.000
MAN: See if anyone’s hurt!

18:06.000 --> 18:08.667
I’m going to step out
for a sec

18:08.667 --> 18:13.583
while Dionne continues rubbing
all of your worries away.

18:13.583 --> 18:15.083
MAN: Go! Hurry!

18:15.083 --> 18:16.625
MAN: Help!
WOMAN: Oh, my God!

18:16.625 --> 18:18.750
WOMAN: Somebody help! Please!

18:18.750 --> 18:20.125
MASSEUSE: Call 911!

18:20.125 --> 18:22.834
Put down the beef bowl
and call 911!

18:22.834 --> 18:25.875
All you have to do is breathe.

18:25.875 --> 18:27.250
EMT: He’s not breathing!

18:28.333 --> 18:29.583
Sounds like everyone

18:29.583 --> 18:32.500
needs to remember
to breathe today.

18:32.500 --> 18:34.583
(sirens blaring)

18:38.125 --> 18:40.750
Wow, you really are tight here.

18:40.750 --> 18:43.208
Oh, so are you.

18:43.208 --> 18:44.542
Why so stressed?

18:44.542 --> 18:48.625
Oh, you know, first kid,
got to get a new roof...

18:48.625 --> 18:50.291
someone’s dying outside.

18:50.291 --> 18:51.667
You don’t know that.

18:51.667 --> 18:53.834
EMT: Keep moving!
That one’s gone!

18:53.834 --> 18:56.333
DIONNE:
Again, we don’t know.

18:56.333 --> 18:58.792
He could be talking
about a parking spot.

18:58.792 --> 19:00.625
EMT: Make way!
Medic’s coming through!

19:00.625 --> 19:02.625
EMT: You need more help?
MAN: Yeah!

19:02.625 --> 19:03.834
GREG: You know, I’m sorry.

19:03.834 --> 19:06.125
I really feel like
I should go out and see...

19:06.125 --> 19:09.417
Ohhh, wow!

19:09.417 --> 19:11.083
EMT: Sir, do not go near
that power line!

19:11.083 --> 19:12.583
(electrical crackling)

19:12.583 --> 19:14.917
EMT: We got a live one!

19:14.917 --> 19:16.750
MAN: Not anymore.

19:16.750 --> 19:17.875
Oh, my...

19:17.875 --> 19:20.208
I’m going to turn up
some of those

19:20.208 --> 19:23.083
soothing nature sounds,
just a bit.

19:24.208 --> 19:25.375
JEN:
Hey, you know what?

19:25.375 --> 19:28.709
Is there, like,
a heavy metal pan flute option?

19:30.041 --> 19:32.208
(gentle music playing)

19:32.208 --> 19:34.041
(mechanical grinding outside)

19:34.041 --> 19:35.458
Yeah, that’s better.

19:39.041 --> 19:42.166
No, that--that’s
the Jaws of Life, honey.

19:42.166 --> 19:44.417
(helicopter approaching)

19:44.417 --> 19:46.583
That must be
the Medevac helicopter.

19:46.583 --> 19:49.250
They only send that in
when there’s a chance.

19:49.250 --> 19:51.291
(helicopter departing)

19:53.500 --> 19:55.291
I guess they forgot something.

19:58.750 --> 20:02.959
♪

20:07.834 --> 20:09.959
JOAN: Oh. Hi!

20:09.959 --> 20:11.375
How was the massage?

20:11.375 --> 20:12.959
JEN:
Oh, life-changing.

20:12.959 --> 20:14.875
-For a lot of people.
-We just--

20:14.875 --> 20:17.959
we realized how lucky
we are to have our health

20:17.959 --> 20:21.500
and each other
and Lark and you.

20:21.500 --> 20:25.041
Oh, you’re so centered!

20:25.041 --> 20:27.625
Now I wish I’d used
the gift certificate.

20:27.625 --> 20:29.458
-No, you don’t.
-No.

20:29.458 --> 20:32.000
-How was Lark?
-Oh, wonderful.

20:32.000 --> 20:34.083
We did a big art project.

20:34.083 --> 20:35.250
Didn’t we?

20:37.542 --> 20:39.208
(snores)

20:39.208 --> 20:40.959
♪

20:41.834 --> 20:48.750
♪
